XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two vehicle daytime collision occurred shortly before noon on an east/west roadway. The roadway is undivided, dry, asphalt, and consists of four lanes. The roadway has a 4% upgrade slope as it travels east. A private driveway exists along its north curb. The roadway is designated a 56 kmph (35 mph) zone.
Vehicle one (V1) is a 2005 Ford F-150, pickup truck, driven by a fifty (50) year old male with one passenger. V1 was traveling eastbound in the number two lane. Vehicle two (V2) is a 1991 Toyota MR2, two-door hatchback, driven by a twenty six (26) year old male. V2 was traveling westbound in the number one lane. As V1 attempted to turn left into a private driveway, the front plane of V2 contacted its right plane. V1 rotated clockwise until contacting the north curb with its right plane. V1 continued rotating as it traveled unto the sidewalk. The right plane of V1 contacted a traffic barrier post and a wooden fence. V1 came to rest facing southwest, blocking the driveway and sidewalk. V2 rotated clockwise and came to rest facing eastbound, blocking the westbound number two lane. Both vehicles were towed due to major damage.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle traveling, turning left at intersection. The critical reason for the critical event was coded to V1 as a driver related factor: misjudgment of gap or other's speed. Medication taken by the driver of V1 was Toprol, he has high blood pressure. The driver was listening to the radio while traveling on an errand from home to a market. He observed V2 to be at a distance when he began his turn into the driveway.
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded: other vehicle encroachment; from opposite direction, over left lane line. Critical reason not coded to this vehicle.
